        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-08-11T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-02-16T08:00:00-05:00" n="114" subtype="editorial-note"
                type="document" xml:id="d114">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>In the evening of May 5, <persName corresp="#p_EA1">Eden</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName> met for dinner, during the course of
                    which substantive discussions on Korea and Indochina took place. <persName
                        corresp="#p_EA1">Eden</persName> gave an account of the meeting to <persName
                        corresp="#p_SWB1">Smith</persName>, who reported to the Department in
                    telegram <gloss target="#t_Secto1">Secto</gloss> 115, May 6, not printed. The
                    telegram contained the following brief passage on Korea: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“<persName corresp="#p_EA1">Eden</persName> said he was not optimistic
                            over prospects of any settlement on Korea unless Russians could prevail
                            upon Chinese and North Koreans to abandon their wholly unreasonable
                            attitude. He did not envisage this happening but thought continuation of
                                <hi rend="italic">status quo</hi> in Korea not too bad. <persName
                                corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName> indicated agreement.” (396.1
                            GE/5–654)</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
            </div>
        </body>
